The 40th President of the United States was Ronald Reagan. He served as President from 1981 to 1989. Prior to his Presidency, Reagan was a Hollywood actor and served as Governor of California from 1967 to 1975. During his Presidency, Reagan implemented conservative economic policies known as "Reaganomics," which included tax cuts and deregulation. He also played a key role in the end of the Cold War, by negotiating with the Soviet Union and advocating for increased defense spending. Reagan is widely regarded as one of the most significant Presidents of the 20th century.